Genomic REML analysis

Source: R/genomic_reml.R
greml.Rd

Genomic restricted maximum likelihood estimation (REML) is an analysis used to estimate genomic and residual variance. Genomic variance is the variance associated with the genomic relationship matrix.

greml(y = NULL, X = NULL, GRMlist = NULL, G = NULL, theta = NULL,
  ids = NULL, validate = NULL, maxit = 100, tol = 1e-05,
  bin = NULL, ncores = 1, wkdir = getwd(), verbose = FALSE,
  makeplots = FALSE, interface = "R")

Arguments

y

vector of phenotypes
X

design matrix of fixed effects
GRMlist

list of information about G matrix
G

genomic relationship matrix
theta

initial values for reml estimation
ids

vector of subsetted individuals to retain for analysis, e.g. cross validation
maxit

maximum number of iterations of reml analysis
tol

tolerance, i.e. the maximum allowed difference between two consecutive iterations of reml to declare convergence
bin

executable file in fortran
ncores

number of cores
wkdir

working directory

Value

Returns a list structure, fit, including

llik

log-likelihood at convergence

theta

initial values for reml estimation

asd

asymptotic standard deviation

b

vector of fixed effect estimates

varb

vector of variances of fixed effect estimates

u

vector of random effect estimates

e

vector of residual effects

Vy

product of variance-covariance matrix of y at convergence and y

Py

product of projection matrix of y and y

trPG

trace of product of projection matrix of y and G

trVG

trace of product of variance-covariance matrix of y at convergence and G

y

vector of phenotypes

X

design matrix of fixed effects

ids

vector of subsetted individuals retained for analysis

yVy

product of y, variance-covariance matrix of y at convergence, and y

fnamesG

filename(s) and locations of of G

wd

working directory

GRMlist

list of information about G matrix

Details

Linear mixed model (LMM) that models covariance among individuals using realized relationships at genotyped loci. This modeling scheme is achieved through the genomic relationship matrix (G). This matrix can be inputted 'as is' or with a more efficient list structure, GRMlist, that contains information about G. The model can accomodate fixed effects. Individuals may be subsetted for additional analyses such as cross validation.

References

Lee, S. H., & van Der Werf, J. H. (2006). An efficient variance component approach implementing an average information REML suitable for combined LD and linkage mapping with a general complex pedigree. Genetics Selection Evolution, 38(1), 25.

Examples


# Simulate data
W <- matrix(rnorm(20000000), ncol = 10000)
        colnames(W) <- as.character(1:ncol(W))
        rownames(W) <- as.character(1:nrow(W))
y <- rowSums(W[, 1:10]) + rowSums(W[, 1001:1010]) + rnorm(nrow(W))

# Create model
data <- data.frame(y = y, mu = 1)
fm <- y ~ 0 + mu
X <- model.matrix(fm, data = data)

# Create framework for lists
setsGB <- list(A = colnames(W)) # gblup model
setsGF <- list(C1 = colnames(W)[1:1000], C2 = colnames(W)[1001:2000], C3 = colnames(W)[2000:10000]) # gfblup model
setsGT <- list(C1 = colnames(W)[1:10], C2 = colnames(W)[1001:1010], C3 = colnames(W)[1:10000]) # true model

# Compute G
G <- computeG(W = W)
GB <- lapply(setsGB, function(x) {computeG(W = W[, x])})
GF <- lapply(setsGF, function(x) {computeG(W = W[, x])})
GT <- lapply(setsGT, function(x) {computeG(W = W[, x])})

# REML analyses
fitGB <- greml(y = y, X = X, G = GB, verbose = TRUE)
